<HEADLINE>
<P>
MORNING REPORT: MOVIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Shauna Snow, Arts and entertainment reports from The Times, national and 
international news services and the nation's press. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The June 3 massacre in Beijing is having lasting effects in Hollywood. An 
agreement between Gibraltar Releasing Corp. and China Film Corp. calling for 
the Cannes Film Festival hit, "Rising Storm," to be the first film released 
simultaneously in the United States and China has been scrapped and locations 
for another Gibraltar film, "Crime Lords," have been shifted from Beijing to 
Taipei and Hong Kong. Director Frankie Schaeffer and "Rising Storm" star Wayne 
Crawford were in Beijing in late May, and departed the country just prior to 
the June 3 government crackdown. "The atmosphere in China was very open and 
very exciting when we left," said Crawford, "but now, China is not the place to 
be working on location for three months." Shauna Snow 
</P>
</TEXT>
