<HEADLINE>
<P>
IN BRIEF: SCIENCE / MEDICINE; 
</P>
<P>
JAVA MAY HINDER EX-SMOKERS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Compiled from staff and wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Researchers at San Francisco General Hospital reported last week that smokers 
who recently kicked the habit may be unusually sensitive to caffeine, 
suggesting that their tendency to be anxious and irritable from nicotine 
withdrawal may be magnified by a cup of java. 
</P>
<P>
Dr. Neal Benowitz and his colleagues studied 68 men and women who were going to 
try to quit smoking. The amount of caffeine in the blood of those who stopped 
smoking was more than 2 1/2 times higher after they quit than before, even 
though their caffeine consumption remained the same or even decreased, the 
researchers reported in the British Medical Journal. By comparison, there was 
no change in the amount of caffeine in the blood of those who did not quit, the 
researchers said. 
</P>
<P>
The tar in cigarette smoke is believed to accelerate the breakdown of a number 
of drugs, including caffeine, said Benowitz, so when someone quits smoking, the 
caffeine may not be broken down as quickly. 
</P>
</TEXT>
