<HEADLINE>
<P>
BRIEFLY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
William Hunt Files Plan: William Herbert Hunt, one of two former billionaire 
sons of wildcat oilman H. L. Hunt who is under protection from creditors, has 
filed a reorganization plan in bankruptcy court that would pay less than half 
of the $300 million in back taxes that the government claims he owes. The 
Internal Revenue Service, Hunt's largest creditor, previously has said it would 
settle for about $150 million, but Hunt's most recent plan would pay the IRS 
$120 million -- half from the proceeds of a liquidating trust and half from 
earnings after he emerges from bankruptcy. Meanwhile, a Peruvian mining company 
filed a plan with the U.S. Bankruptcy Court in Dallas saying it would settle 
for $80 million of the $132 million it lost on Hunt's failed silver 
speculation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, William Herbert Hunt 
</P>
</GRAPHIC>
