<P>
SWEDEN'S RAILWAY WORKERS STRIKE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
STOCKHOLM 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Swedish railway workers, demanding a $300-a-month pay hike, staged a wildcat 
strike today that shut down most train service and jammed highways with 
commuters trying to drive to work. 
</P>
<P>
Managers at Swedish Rail were attempting to keep as many commuter trains in 
service as possible, but only 10% of the country's trains were in operation, a 
spokesman said. 
</P>
<P>
Commuters clogged highways in an attempt to get to work, and a spokesman for 
the national road service said cars were backed up for miles along the roads to 
most major cities. Airport officials said three times the regular number of 
people were trying to book tickets on domestic flights. 
</P>
<P>
The nation's 3,300 train drivers were striking to press their demands for a 
$300 per month pay hike and force the Social Democratic government to withdraw 
plans to increase the pension age from 60 to 65. 
</P>
</TEXT>
